      Private credit
   =20
 =20
Just from first principles it is weird that, if you are a company or a priv=
ate equity sponsor looking to borrow a lot of money, and you go to a gigant=
ic bank like J.P. Morgan Chase & Co., the bank will say =E2=80=9Cyes, I wou=
ld be happy to help you find that money.=E2=80=9D Whereas if you go to an a=
lternative asset manager like Blue Owl Capital or Ares Management Corp., th=
e alternative asset manager will pull out a bag with a dollar sign on it an=
d say =E2=80=9Cyes, here is=C2=A0money.=E2=80=9D If you asked the average p=
erson =E2=80=9Cwho has more money, JPMorgan Chase or Blue Owl,=E2=80=9D the=
y would probably say =E2=80=9CI guess the biggest bank in America has more =
money than a company I have never heard of.=E2=80=9D Also they would be rig=
ht! JPMorgan has $4 trillion of assets; Blue Owl manages about $174 billion=
.=C2=A0And yet from the perspective of a private equity sponsor, JPMorgan i=
s in the business of=C2=A0intermediating loans:=C2=A0When you go to a big b=
ank to get financing for a leveraged buyout, the bank will work with you to=
 market the debt and find investors to buy it; you don=E2=80=99t expect the=
 bank to buy most of the debt itself.
  [1]
=C2=A0Whereas Blue Owl is in the business of=C2=A0providing loans: You go t=
o a private credit manager because you expect it to just hand you the money=
. Obviously it too is an intermediary =E2=80=94=C2=A0that money doesn=E2=80=
=99t just=C2=A0belong=C2=A0to Blue Owl; that money is in funds that it mana=
