The way credit ratings work is:=09A company wants people to think that it=
=E2=80=99s creditworthy. It might want to issue bonds or insurance policies=
, and it knows that people will only lend it money or buy its insurance if =
they think it=E2=80=99s good for the money.=09There are firms =E2=80=94=C2=
=A0=E2=80=9Cratings agencies,=E2=80=9D =E2=80=9Cnationally recognized stati=
stical rating organizations=E2=80=9D =E2=80=94=C2=A0that give companies cre=
dit ratings on some well-known scale. All the relevant parties know=C2=A0th=
at a bond rated =E2=80=9CAa1=E2=80=9D or an insurance company rated =E2=80=
=9CA+=E2=80=9D is a safe bet, while one rated =E2=80=9CCa2=E2=80=9D or =E2=
=80=9CC=E2=80=9D is riskier.=09These ratings firms go around giving ratings=
 to companies.=09Specifically, though, they go around giving ratings to com=
panies=C2=A0that hire them=C2=A0to give them ratings. The way a company get=
s a rating is by calling up a ratings firm, saying =E2=80=9Chey can you giv=
e us a rating,=E2=80=9D entering into a customer relationship, and=C2=A0pay=
ing=C2=A0the ratings firm for the rating.The conflicts of interest embedded=
 in this system are extremely well known and sometimes blamed for the 2008 =
financial crisis. But one should not overstate them. Sure, right, the compa=
nies are the customers and pay the ratings firms for the ratings; there is =
a customer relationship, and if the ratings firm gives the customer a bad r=
ating (1) that will be awkward and the ratings firm will get yelled at and =
(2) it might=C2=A0lose the customer relationship=C2=A0and, thus, money.But =
on the other hand, the ratings firms=C2=A0are=C2=A0aware that they are play=
ing a long game. The way to maximize revenue=C2=A0this week=C2=A0might be t=
o call up every company and say =E2=80=9Chey if you double our fee we=E2=80=
=99ll give you an AAA+ rating,=E2=80=9D but if you actually do that, then y=
our ratings will lose all credibility with the market, and by=C2=A0next wee=
k=C2=A0nobody will want to pay you for them. (Also ratings agencies are reg=
ulated by the US Securities and Exchange Commission, which pays a *lot* of =
attention to this conflict, so you=E2=80=99ll get in trouble with the SEC i=
f you do this.)And so the actual incentives of the ratings firms encourage =
something like =E2=80=9Cgood customer service combined with credibility.=E2=
=80=9D Exactly what that means will vary, but I think that=C2=A0one=C2=A0th=
ing it means is: If you are a ratings firm, you will want to be at least a =
little bit ahead of any disasters. What you don=E2=80=99t want, after the e=
xperience of 2008, is news stories like =E2=80=9Ceven as XYZ Corp. was slid=
ing into bankruptcy, its bonds remained rated AA-.=E2=80=9D That is very sa=
lient, and very bad for your credibility. If you downgrade the bonds to B- =
a week before the bankruptcy, you at least avoid those headlines. Arguably =
your incentives are something like:=09Be a=C2=A0touch=C2=A0generous to most=
 of your clients most of the time, and=09Be=C2=A0really harsh=C2=A0on clien=
ts who you worry might be skating toward disaster.One ratings-firm incentiv=
e that I had never really appreciated before, though, is:=09If you=E2=80=99=
re a ratings agency, the company that you=E2=80=99re rating is your client.=
=09You have some sort of client agreement with them, probably promising tha=
t you=E2=80=99ll do a good and honest job of rating them.=09If they disagre=
e with your rating,=C2=A0they can sue you.777 Partners is an investment fir=
m that has been trying to buy the English Premier League team Everton FC. E=
arlier this month, a lender to 777 called Leadenhall Capital Partners=C2=A0=
filed an absolutely wild lawsuit against it, claiming that it had borrowed =
hundreds of millions of dollars secured by assets that=C2=A0it didn=E2=80=
=99t own or that it had pledged to multiple lenders. (Here is the extremely=
 fun complaint, featuring an anonymous tip and alleged recorded confessions=
 of guilt.) The lawsuit also alleged that an insurance company called Advan=
tage Capital Holdings, known as A-Cap, had loaned 777 billions of dollars a=
nd was secretly controlling it; =E2=80=9Ca=C2=A0representative for A-Cap sa=
id the claims made by Leadenhall are =E2=80=98sensational and unfounded.=E2=
=80=99=E2=80=9DA-Cap gets financial ratings from A.M. Best Rating Services =
Inc., a nationally recognized statistical rating organization. Two A-Cap co=
mpanies, Atlantic Coast Life Insurance and Sentinel Security Life Insurance=
, have A.M. Best financial strength ratings of B++, which is =E2=80=9Cgood.=
=E2=80=9D In March, apparently to get=C2=A0out ahead of the 777 stuff, A.M.=
 Best decided to downgrade them to B-, which is =E2=80=9Cfair.=E2=80=9D And=
 the insurance companies=C2=A0sued to stop the downgrade. This week, the Fi=
nancial Times reports:AM Best, the specialist rating agency for the insuran=
ce sector, has said its credibility risks being =E2=80=9Cirreparably damage=
