but those holders naturally delegate the work to people with more interest =
in doing it.=C2=A0</p><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">If you hold Ether you do=
n=E2=80=99t=C2=A0<em>have=C2=A0</em>to be involved in any of this =E2=80=94=
=C2=A0=E2=80=9Cabout 27% of the all outstanding Ether is staked,=E2=80=9D r=
eports Shen =E2=80=94=C2=A0but it is kind of free money? If you hold dollar=
s, you don=E2=80=99t=C2=A0<em>have=C2=A0</em>to put them in a high-yield sa=
vings account or a money market fund, but for a lot people that would make =
sense. Ethereum staking rewards, to many Ether holders, look more or less l=
ike bank account interest.</p><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Next: =E2=80=9CQ=
uestions about whether the token should be treated as a security that falls=
 under the purview of US regulators.=E2=80=9D There are a couple of levels =
of this. One is: If I run a staking=C2=A0<em>program</em>, in which I do th=
e validating stuff and pay you a cut of the staking rewards, is=C2=A0<em>th=
at offering=C2=A0</em>a security? In practice, many of the people who run s=
taking programs are=C2=A0<em>crypto exchanges</em>, for pretty natural reas=
ons: Crypto exchanges have lots of retail customers who buy and hold Ether =
on their platforms. The exchanges are holding the customers=E2=80=99 Ether =
anyway. If they can put that Ether to work doing staking, they can earn an =
interest-like return on it, and then pass a lot of that interest on to thei=
r customers, making the customers happy. It=E2=80=99s a good product.</p><p=
 style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">But the US Securities and Exchange Commission un=
ambiguously believes that that product is a=C2=A0<em>security</em>, that th=
e customers who deposit their Ether with Coinbase or Kraken or whomever, wi=
