</table><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">A common approach in many creative fie=
lds is that you spend a lot of time thinking about a problem, learning its =
details, saturating yourself in it and=C2=A0trying to find solutions. And t=
hen you stop thinking about it and go off and do something else, and that=
=E2=80=99s when you find the solution. =E2=80=9C<a href=3D"https://link.mai=
l.bloombergbusiness.com/click/35478826.261334/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cudGhlYXRsYW50a=
WMuY29tL3ZpZGVvL2FyY2hpdmUvMjAxNS8xMS90aGVyZS1pcy1hLWNyZWF0aXZlLXB1cnBvc2Ut=
dG8tZGF5ZHJlYW1pbmctZXZlbi1ib3JlZG9tLzYyNTcyMi8/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cB3f=
3c914f" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"itemscope" target=3D"_blank" st=
yle=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !important; border-bottom-widt=
h: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: solid; backgroun=
d-color: #ccc;">The three B=E2=80=99s</a>,=E2=80=9D it is sometimes called:=
 The answers tend to come in bed, the bath or the bus. Active focused think=
ing cannot fully solve the problem; you need a contribution from some eleme=
nt of the subsconscious mind.</p><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Is investing =
like that? Or weirder? Is the right approach to spend all day examining a s=
tock, and then go to bed and see if you dream of it? I don=E2=80=99t know b=
ut=C2=A0<a href=3D"https://link.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/click/35478826.2=
61334/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cucG5hcy5vcmcvZG9pL2Ficy8xMC4xMDczL3BuYXMuMjMwNzk4MjEyM=
Q/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cB7f1e77a8" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"it=
emscope" target=3D"_blank" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !=
important; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-b=
ottom-style: solid; background-color: #ccc;">here=E2=80=99s a wild paper</a=
>:</p><blockquote><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">The investors=E2=80=99 dream=
 of forecasting the stock market is typically considered to be just that: a=
n unrealistic aspiration. However, we find that forecasting stock performan=
ce may in fact not be completely unattainable. Results of our neuroimaging =
experiment reveal that professional investors fail to accurately predict lo=
ng-term stock performance. However, while processing complex information pe=
rtaining to investment cases, brain activity in a region associated with re=
ward anticipation was increased for stocks that would end up overperforming=
 in the future market. Remarkably, this effect held after controlling for t=
he stock information presented in the investment cases. Our findings add to=
 recent work in =E2=80=9Cneuroforecasting,=E2=80=9D demonstrating that mark=
et behavior can be forecasted by brain activity of a small sample, here of =
professional investors.</p></blockquote><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">That=
=E2=80=99s =E2=80=9CBrain activity of professional investors signals future=
 stock performance,=E2=80=9D by Leonard van Brussel, Maarten Boksem, Roelan=
d Dietvorst and Ale Smidts, who seem to be business professors (and an inve=
stor), not neurosurgeons. (There=E2=80=99s a <a href=3D"https://link.mail.b=
loombergbusiness.com/click/35478826.261334/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuYmlvcnhpdi5vcmcv=
Y29udGVudC8xMC4xMTAxLzIwMjMuMDUuMDMuNTM5MDYydjE/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cB85=
e15621" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"itemscope" target=3D"_blank" st=
yle=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !important; border-bottom-widt=
h: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: solid; backgroun=
d-color: #ccc;">free version of the paper here</a>.) =E2=80=9CAs investors =
processed case information, nucleus accumbens (NAcc) activity was higher fo=
r investment cases that ended up overperforming in the market. =E2=80=9D Th=
e takeaway, I think, is that if you run a hedge fund, you should:</p><ol st=
yle=3D"list-style-type: decimal; padding-left: 40px; margin: 16px 0;">=09<l=
i style=3D"margin-bottom: 5px;">hire skilled experienced portfolio managers=
,</li>=09<li style=3D"margin-bottom: 5px;">have ChatGPT=C2=A0write up simpl=
e investment memos=C2=A0for various stocks,</li>=09<li style=3D"margin-bott=
om: 5px;">pop the portfolio managers into an MRI machine,</li>=09<li style=
=3D"margin-bottom: 5px;">read ChatGPT=E2=80=99s memos to the portfolio mana=
gers,</li>=09<li style=3D"margin-bottom: 5px;">ask the portfolio managers =
=E2=80=9Cwhat do you think,=E2=80=9D and</li>=09<li style=3D"margin-bottom:=
 5px;">ignore what they say and just buy the stocks that make their nucleus=
 accumbens light up.</li></ol><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">This is not inve=
sting=C2=A0or medical advice, and frankly it seems like it might be hard to=
 hire good investors on those terms. But the result that professional inves=
tors are better at picking stocks <em>unconsciously </em>than <em>conscious=
ly</em> is pretty weird.</p><table class=3D"header" width=3D"100%" border=
